04325nam a22005415i 9780889205598DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061999xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892055987 a10.51644/97808892055982doi  a(DE-B1597)667828  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1455.T87bA3 1999eb 7aREL1050002bisacsh04a305.42/092qOCoLC04aThe Life and Letters of Annie Leake Tuttle :bWorking for the Best /ced. by Marilyn Färdig Whiteley. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (164 p.) :b(illus.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLife Writing00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Simple Life 1839-1849 -- tTwo Homes 1849-1856 -- tTurning Points 1856-1858 -- tSerious Undertakings 1858-1866 -- tAbove My Highest Dreams 1866-1887 -- tRemarkable Years 1887-1895 -- tA New Position 1895-1902 -- tWaiting on the Lord 1902-1907 -- tA Place to Call Home 1907-1917 -- tTime Enough 1917-1934 -- tEpilogue 1934 -- tChildren of Thomas Leake and Olevia Lockhart -- tAnnie Leake Turtle—Chronology -- tSources -- tBooks in the Life Writing Series Published0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnnie Leake Tuttle was born in Nova Scotia in 1839 and died there in 1934, yet her search for education and self-support took her far afield. During her life she filled important positions from Newfoundland to British Columbia, as an educator of teachers and as the matron of a Methodist rescue home for Chinese immigrant women who had worked as prostitutes. Her autobiography paints a vivid picture of the joys and hardships of growing up on a pioneer farm and documents her spiritual and educational quests and conquests. In addition, readers see the independence and strength of character that enable Annie Tuttle to take on family obligations that fall to an unmarried daughter and sister, and to meet the challenges of step-motherhood, the adjustments of aging and ultimately the prospect of death. Marilyn Färdig Whiteley gently frames Tuttle’s autobiography by placing it into social and historical context. She delineates the way in which Annie claimed her identity as she began to record her life story and demonstrates how her evangelical faith enabled her to show, in her narrative, that “One above” was always “working for the best,” helping her in the work she was intended to do. In The Life of Annie Leake Tuttle: Working for the Best, we find a rich collection of the writings of an articulate woman who shows herself to be both ordinary and extraordinary. It is a fascinating chronicle of the spiritual and secular life of an independent and spirited woman in early Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLife Writing. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aRELIGION / Sexuality & Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aWhiteley, Marilyn Färdig, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920559840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889205598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889205598/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles